metadata.name: Artifact #224
metadata.description:
This project is about uncovering artifacts.

Each piece is determined by approximately 15 parameters. This allows for a multitude of possible forms, and each iteration is an artifact to be discovered within the multidimensional space.

This work is focused around discovery. It is about exploring the space of the algorithm, shedding light on its many forms, and sometimes finding artifacts of the real world embedded within them.

Technically, this work is a composition of three primary elements: Voronoi tessellations, orthographic projection, and the depth-sort algorithm.
The latter of these is integral to the rendering mechanism. It works intuitively, drawing distant objects before near objects, evaluating the distance of each object according to its geometric center. It does this precisely, and in doing so, it can produce interesting visual artifacts, drawing some shapes in an unexpected order.



This has been a fascinating study, bringing light to unreal shapes and forms, and uncovering artifacts in an impossible space.

I hope you enjoy it,
Nat Sarkissian





Technical Notes:
- Append ‚Äú&mag=N‚Äù to the end of the URL in live mode to specify a resolution multiplier. It will render the image N times larger than the size of your window. If you have specified anything greater than 1, a download will start automatically once the rendering is done.

metadata.name: Sierras #31
metadata.description:
This is meant to look like a hand drawn map you might find in a fantasy book. It's also inspired by the landscapes I've seen along the California coast and the Sierra Nevada mountains.

In live mode, once the art is generated, tap the 's' key to save a large version of it.

Enjoy!

metadata.name: SquareCuts #31
metadata.description:
For my third project, a simple square is cut into small pieces that are rotated, moved or softened.
By playing on these parameters, we obtain many results with interesting aspects. Seven output families are possible.

metadata.name: Glossolalia #222
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse‚Ä¶ which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it‚Äôs about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It‚Äôs less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append ‚Äú&density=2‚Äù to the url to double the size, ‚Äú&density=3‚Äù to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append ‚Äú&grain=##‚Äù to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: gradient descent #130
metadata.description:
Whether by choice or circumstance, we often find our lives thrust into uncertainty. We're resilient, though ‚Äî we find patterns in the chaos, deciphering and unraveling it piece by piece until a new comfort emerges. `gradient descent` is my expression of that cyclical flow that comes to dominate our lives.

The piece starts with comfort, a smooth gradient chosen from a curated palette. As the animation runs, that gradient is mutated by a unique sequence of linear transformations - slice, skew or stride on an underlying grid - as it descends into uncertainty. After a time the animation will reverse, peeling back each transformation and returning to comfort before beginning anew.

The menu - which can be accessed with a double click or Escape - gives you extensive control of the experience. I'd encourage you to explore these settings ‚Äî they transform the feel of the piece, allowing you to adapt it to match your environment or mood. Any setting that can be changed in the menu can also be provided as a URL parameter - there's a button in the menu to export them all.

Built with raw WebGL 1.0, optimised to run smoothly on most devices.

Best viewed in full screen on large format displays.

||| controls

[hold space] ‚áù speed up
[esc/2xclick] ‚áù toggle menu
[g] ‚áù toggle gallery mode
[p] ‚áù toggle pause
[s] ‚áù capture current frame
[a] ‚áù capture all keyframes
[8/9/0/-] ‚áù change viewport

||| settings

All settings are configurable via the interactive menu. Initial values can be set as url parameters by adding &[name]=[value] to the url.

loop [1|0, default 1]
|  ‚áù  loop the animation
infinite [1|0, default 0]
|  ‚áù  generate a new sequence after each descent, constantly evolving
gallery [1|0, default 0]
|  ‚áù  display in gallery mode with keyframes
quality [#, default 1]
|  ‚áù  additional dpr scaling - lower to improve animation smoothness
speed [#, default 1]
|  ‚áù  multiplier for step animation speed
step-pause [#, default 0.35]
|  ‚áù  seconds to pause between keyframe steps
start-pause [#, default 4]
|  ‚áù  seconds to pause at the initial keyframe
end-pause [#, default 4]
|  ‚áù  seconds to pause at the final keyframe

||| capture

Capture current frame saves the still immediately, while capture all keyframes saves each of the keyframes sequentially. Some browsers may require confirmation to save multiple stills. When triggered early, unrendered keyframes will be blank. All captures are impacted by the following settings.

capture-aspect [#, default 1]
|  ‚áù  aspect ratio of the capture, as width/height
capture-size [#, default 2048]
|  ‚áù  longest dimension of the captures to save, in pixels

metadata.name: Primordial #106
metadata.description:
Primordial is a study of abstract forms. The algorithm, written in p5.js and WebGL, utilizes domain warping to create twisted fields of color and then overlays thousands of tiny lines to provide depth and texture. The outputs are chaotic but not completely formless, like a swirling mass of plasma from the early universe, or a strange proto-life form suspended in prehistoric ooze.

CONTROLS:

1-9: Increase resolution and save image in PNG format

B: Toggle borders on/off

F: Fullscreen
P: Portrait
L: Landscape
S: Square

For third party license information, please see license.md

David Brice Allen
October 2022

metadata.name: Dualidad #55
metadata.description:
The concept of 'Dualidad' (duality) is brought to life through the use of opposing elements, circles, and rectangles, in the artwork. 

The circles, like the stillness of a calm pond, remain in close places while they continuously transform. In contrast, the rectangles are a representation of movement and change, constantly traveling across the canvas. 

This balance of opposing elements creates a dynamic tension that draws the viewer in, leaving them mesmerized by the ever-evolving artwork. Expect to see a range of emotions, from the euphoria of joy to the depth of sorrow, as you explore the duality of this project.

-----

The generative process of each artwork has a typical completion time ranging from 20 seconds to 2 minutes, depending on your PC.

-----

Tested on Brave, Opera and Mozilla (Linux systems). Brave and Safari (macOS)


-----

Press "e" to save a high res png while in live mode.

-----

Artwork by @cristianrohr (2023)

Made with P5js and <3

metadata.name: CELDAS #259
metadata.description:
Cells, called "CELDAS" in Spanish, are spaces separated by lines or stripes in a geometric structure. Generally, cells are formed when the stripes intersect to form a mesh or grid. Each cell formed by these stripes can be filled with a color to create a design.
I love the way I can play with the horizontality and verticality of the stripes to create unique and original geometric patterns, and how through different sizes of stripes an infinity of pieces are formed ranging from the minimalist and sophisticated to the most colorful and expressive, bringing each piece a fresh and current air within a vibrant color palette.
The DNA of this collection is my passion for stripes and colors, both united in a single project that reflects my love in each piece.
I hope you enjoy it as much as I do!

metadata.name: Isola della Scala #84
metadata.description:
All things pass, all things flow,
Movement, connection, separation, all in tow.
A misstep and we're knocked off course,
But in the end, we rise, as if by force.
Like a dance of dominoes, we fall and we stand,
In this ever-changing world, we're a part of the grand.

The name of this work is the name of the city where my roots began, where the path of everything changed and new directions in life were taken.

Made with p5.js, p5.grain and much love

metadata.name: Adjacent #109
metadata.description:
Adjacent is the third in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art. This piece focuses on the study of Diagonal White, a series he developed between 1970 and 1975.

In 1976, Ruth Leavitt published a collection of papers titled "Artist & Computer", which highlighted the 35 prominent generative artists and asked them to discuss their work. They were posed questions like, "Do you feel art work created with a computer has now or will have an impact on art as a whole in the future?". Edward Zajec was a subject of one of those papers and in it detailed the approach to Diagonal White. 

The original program was run on a CDC 6200 computer at The Univeresiry of Trieste. The programming was done in collaboration with Dr. Matjaz Hmeljak, his long-time technical partner. Inspired by his collaborative relationship, Adjacent the output of a partnership between Christine Hall and Chris Maddern.

Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to save a high-resolution version of the image

Made in p5js
Created January 2023
By @christine_hall and @chrismaddern

metadata.name: Element #124
metadata.description:
Element is a generative series of pixelated mosaics that explores two contrasting styles of generative art. One style embraces imperfection and noise to simulate paint or other real-life textures, while the other produces digital outputs with precise forms.

The mosaics were inspired by the works of Hiroshi Kawano, one of the pioneers of generative art. They are generated by randomly placing rectangles inside a grid then applying a Markov-chain process multiple times. A hand-drawn and organic style is then incorporated using various techniques such drawing many rectangles with subtle variations in colour for a paint texture or adding different kinds of noise.

Please view in full-screen for the best experience.

Press [s] when the output is fully rendered to download it as a png file. The resolution can be set by adding for example "&s=2048" to the url for a 2048 x 2048 output.

Element was released as part of the Cure3 exhibition, generating vital funds for Cure Parkinson's medical research.

metadata.name: Richter #122
metadata.description:
Richter is the second collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog, following their first project called Gerhard. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time.
 
Richter works with data from 4 of 24 highres images, 30mb in total. This is the maximum size fxhash allows for a project and three times more than Gerhard. Richard Nadler created stunning new textures, enabling more variation in composition and detail to emerge at much higher resolution. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Richter elevates the approach from Gerhard with new methods for the realtime rendering process and new features like offline-first caching. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels as data.
 
Richter is featured in the exhibition "Generative Abstraction" at Expanded.art in Berlin.
 
- Click to start a new layer of motion and color.
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen.
- Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save the canvas.
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

leanderherzog.ch/2023/richter/
leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/
fxhash.xyz/generative/17030/

metadata.name: Composition study : Grid #229
metadata.description: This project explores the use of geometric shapes, specifically grids, cubes, and patterns, in composition. The focus will be on using these shapes and patterns to create dynamic and visually interesting compositions, both in 2D and 3D forms. The project begins by studying the use of grids and how they can be used to create structure and balance in a composition. Next, the use of cubes will be examined, and how they can be used to add depth and dimension to a composition. Finally, the project will delve into the use of patterns and how they can be used to create movement and interest within a composition.

metadata.name: NESTED IDENTITIES #61
metadata.description:
Nested identities redact fingerprints but deeper meaning can still be found.

Nested identifies refers to the idea that a person may have multiple identities that are interconnected and interdependent. These identities may be related to a person's cultural background, ethnicity, nationality, gender, sexual orientation, social class, profession, and other factors. It is possible that a person may want to conceal or redact certain aspects of their identity in order to protect their privacy or to avoid discrimination or persecution. However, even if certain details about a person's identity are hidden or redacted, it may still be possible to infer deeper meaning or understand more about their experiences and perspectives based on the context in which they express themselves and the information that is available.


The concept of nested identities highlights the complexity and multifaceted nature of a person's identity, and how different aspects of identity can intersect and influence each other. It is important to recognize and respect the diversity of identities that people may hold, and to be mindful of the ways in which power dynamics and social context can shape how people present and express their identities. It is also important to recognize that people's identities may evolve and change over time, and that everyone has the right to self-identify and to define their own identity on their own terms.

Press p to download a high quality export.
